沙利頓时，他的父亲William de Irmingland Lord of Whitfoots Hall22岁，母亲Lady William de Irmingland17岁。他于1444年与Katherine Parton of Sharrington在英国諾福爾可沙利頓结婚。他们至少是1个女儿的父母。他去世于1476年在他的家乡享年54岁，埋葬在英国英格兰諾福爾可沙利頓。"},"hr":{"1422–1476":"1422.–1476.","1422–1474":"1422.–1474","1445–1491":"1445.–1491","1400–1476":"1400–1476.","1405–Female":"1405–preminula","1445":"1445.","1422":"1422.","1444":"1444.","1455":"1455","1400":"1400","1476":"1476.","Abt 1474":"oko 1474.","1474":"1474","about 1476":"1476.","1491":"1491","1405":"1405","Sharrington, North Norfolk district, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom":"Sharrington, Norfolk, Engleska, United Kingdom","Sharrington, Norfolk, England":"Sharrington, Norfolk, England","All Saints' Church, Sharrington, North Norfolk district, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom":"Sharrington, Norfolk, Engleska, United Kingdom"},"cs":{"1422–1476":"1422–1476","1422–1474":"1422–1474","1445–1491":"1445–1491","1400–1476":"1400–1476","1405–Female":"1405–Zesnulá","1445":"1445","1422":"1422","1444":"1444","1455":"1455","1400":"1400","1476":"1476","Abt 1474":"okolo 1474","1474":"1474","about 1476":"1476","1491":"1491","1405":"1405","Sharrington, North Norfolk district, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom":"Sharrington, Norfolk, Anglie, United Kingdom","Sharrington, Norfolk, England":"Sharrington, Norfolk, Anglie","All Saints' Church, Sharrington, North Norfolk district, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom":"Sharrington, Norfolk, Anglie, United Kingdom"},"da":{"1422–1476":"1422–1476","1422–1474":"1422–1474","1445–1491":"1445–1491","1400–1476":"1400–1476","1405–Female":"1405–Afdød","1445":"1445","1422":"1422","1444":"1444","1455":"1455","1400":"1400","1476":"1476","Abt 1474":"omkring 1474","1474":"1474","about 1476":"1476","1491":"1491","1405":"1405","Sharrington, North Norfolk district, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom":"Sharrington, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","Sharrington, Norfolk, England":"Sharrington, Norfolk, England","All Saints' Church, Sharrington, North Norfolk district, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom":"Sharrington, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"1422–1476":"1422–1476","1422–1474":"1422–1474","1445–1491":"1445–1491","1400–1476":"1400–1476","1405–Female":"1405–Overleden","1445":"1445","1422":"1422","1444":"1444","1455":"1455","1400":"1400","1476":"1476","Abt 1474":"circa 1474","1474":"1474","about 1476":"1476","1491":"1491","1405":"1405","Sharrington, North Norfolk district, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom":"Sharrington, Norfolk, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Sharrington, Norfolk, England":"Sharrington, Norfolk, England","All Saints' Church, Sharrington, North Norfolk district, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom":"Sharrington, Norfolk, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1422–1476":"1422–1476","1422–1474":"1422–1474","1445–1491":"1445–1491","1400–1476":"1400–1476","1405–Female":"1405–Deceased","1445":"1445","1422":"1422","1444":"1444","1455":"1455","1400":"1400","1476":"1476","Abt 1474":"about 1474","1474":"1474","about 1476":"1476","1491":"1491","1405":"1405","Sharrington, North Norfolk district, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom":"Sharrington, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","Sharrington, Norfolk, England":"Sharrington, Norfolk, England","All Saints' Church, Sharrington, North Norfolk district, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom":"Sharrington, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":33,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Richard D’Irmingland was born in 1422, in Sharrington, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom, his father, William de Irmingland Lord of Whitfoots Hall, was 22 and his mother, Lady William de Irmingland, was 17. He married Katherine Parton of Sharrington in 1444, in Sharrington, Norfolk, England. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died in 1476, in his hometown, at the age of 54, and was buried in Sharrington, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1422–1476":"1422–1476","1422–1474":"1422–1474","1445–1491":"1445